ced the rights and responsibilities of citizenship, and whether the welfare state still offers meaningful protection and security in times of need. She reflects on the mismatch between the portrayal of ‘welfare’ and everyday experiences, and the consequences of this for the UK’s ongoing welfare reform programme. Exploring issues including the meaning of dependency, the impact of benefit sanctions and the reach of benefits stigma, this important book makes a timely contribution to ongoing debates about the efficacy and ethics of welfare reform.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh1 aLister, Baroness Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831111966330 cprintz978144733348740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447333470423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447333470/original  a978-3-11-119663-3  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles